##I fall asleep on the streets of Wuhan, please don't water my quilt

Southreviews

Functional presentation, the power of calm

The flooded passageway and their luggage were photographed at around 7 p.m. on Feb. 24(photo / South Window reporter, Xiang Zhilin) 

Four days in a row, weather-forecasting software shows that Wuhan will have a prolonged period of rain. But even before the rain began to fall, Gao Qiang's place was soaking wet.

He lives in an underground tunnel in Wuchang District. At a little after 2 p.m. on February 24, more than a dozen people came into the tunnel, connected to a water pipe, and washed the entire floor.

About an hour later, the flusher left, and Gao Qiang went down to "salvage" his luggage.

His luggage was all wet, including the sheets on the floor, a quilt and, two days earlier, a "cotton coat from the Red Cross. ". Reluctant to part with his coat, he took it out and dried it on the iron pole at the entrance and exit.

There were seven people living in the corridor. They were stranded in Wuhan and could not afford a hotel.

As they flushed, they watched as the coverings got wet, but they were afraid to step forward because "the men were wearing law enforcement uniforms. ".

"It's a special time, and we all understand that, " Gao Qiang said. "But a group of us, even living in a passageway, is better than no place to live and run around. ".

Stranded in Wuhan
Gao Qiang lived in the passageway for about 10 days. He came to Wuhan as a migrant worker and did odd jobs on the construction site. After the construction break, the dorm was empty, but he didn't want to go home.

A year, no money, he just want to start early.

Unexpectedly, on January 23, Wuhan "closed the city. ". "There's no going back now, " Gao Qiang said with a wry smile.

First he stayed in a small hotel, charging 30 yuan a day, but the food became more and more expensive, "at least 100 yuan a day. ". He won't be able to afford it much longer.

He thought of two ways, one is to check out of the room, sleep on the street, save a day room fee, can change some more instant noodles. The second is to find work, he guessed, now Wuhan, certainly the lack of labor. He started in Hankou, walked through the neighborhood, asked if anyone needed a temp? If he saw a street sweeper on the road, he would ask if there were any job opportunities?

"No. "
"No need. "

He doesn't know how he got to the underpass. Gao Qiang says he remembers walking with a swollen leg because he was lying on the cold ground and couldn't straighten his back quickly, but he kept walking. When he got to the passageway, he was given a mattress to look at.

He just moved in.

Yellow Crane Tower remains well lit, and the ancient buildings, surrounded by lights, look good at dusk, but not a single visitor is seen. Shortly after 6 p.m. on Feb. 24, I reached the underpass and, three hours after flushing, the water was still running on the ground and the pipe had been left on the stairs. The passage is by the West Gate of the Yellow Crane Tower, and across the road is the memorial of the 1911 Revolution in Wuchang.

The passage was uninhabitable and they had to wander in the woods near the park.

Fang Jian "rescued" a bucket and a bag, which was his food, or "begging" tool. He was a professional beggar and had been begging since 1998. He is from Fuyang, Anhui Province. He is 37 years old.

The sleeve on his right arm was empty, and he had an amputation when he was 15. The doctor said it was osteonecrosis. "I'm sure it can be treated now, but at that time there were no conditions and no money, " he said.

When flushing, Fang Jian loitered in the park, and from time to time stepped up to take a look at them. "They took the tap and flushed it against the quilt, " he said.

His possessions were all down there, but he did not dare to stop them. "They never give us any reason to do anything, " he said. "To be honest, we are all inferior. ".

Soggy Luggage (photo / South Window reporter, Xiang Zhilin)

Another holdout, Sheng Kuan, and Fang Jian are fellow Anhui villagers. He also did temporary work in Wuhan Life, "closed" after no place to go.

He was older and had a more checkered past, working in Shantou before returning to his hometown of Xiangyang for the Spring Festival, but was stuck passing through Wuhan.

Old Tan earlier sent money home, only according to normal projections left a little bit wrapped, this is not enough. When he reported to his family safe, his family said to give him money, but he refused, "was not a few money, their ability to survive. ".

Gao Qiang said the family did not know he was "wandering" , the old home of a 70-year-old mother, fortunately, has his brother to take care of, but she would be worried. Gao Qiang couldn't bring herself to tell her family.

Well, the money's gone. Gao Qiang borrowed $200 from a former worker and spent it a few days later. Every day he looked forward to Wuhan "unsealed" News, but in various rumors, day after day to drag.

"another month and I wouldn't have been able to hold on, " he said.

As Gao Qiang, Fang Jian, and I talked, Tam and Sheng went to the hospital with the last of the instant noodles to soak in boiling water, but at a nearby hospital, barricades were erected to keep them out. They walked back and forth for more than an hour before they were given boiled water at a children's hospital.

Gao Qiang and Fang Jian, without a pack of instant noodles, had been hungry all day.

Gao Qiang said one man began searching for food in the trash, but now, with only food in the hospital bins, "he picked up a box lunch and the others only took a bite or two. I think the food looks good. " Gao Qiang said, but he was afraid to eat it because he was afraid of the virus.

The man in the trash can is young, 27. He was in the park, sitting alone on a bench. He said he had come to Wuhan last September and had been unemployed. He didn't want to talk about anything else.

In fact, they're very wary of outsiders. When I ordered takeout for five people, old Tan and Sheng were slow to arrive. Fang and I circled around, found them by the side of the road, and spotted them eating hot. But they repeatedly refused, saying they had eaten.

Sheng stammered out his reasons, worried about being photographed again. They met a few waves of people, some left them something, immediately crazy photos, "I am a big man, hands and feet have normal work, but during difficult times, give us exposure, too embarrassing. ".

When they were sure they weren't going to take a picture, they felt at ease and picked up their meal.

"If it hadn't been for the virus, we wouldn't be living in the tunnels, " Gao Qiang told me. "Now we're being chased out

Rescue
With no place to live, Gao Qiang worried that if it did rain, it would be harder for them.

We're running out of food. We can't afford it. Strict management, small shops are mostly closed, the supermarket is not open to individuals. They now have food, or a few days ago to buy early, and some of the gifts of the public interest.

Gao Qiang remembered that about 3 groups of people came.

"The second group came on February 21, claiming to be from the Red Cross, and they gave the most, " Gao Qiang said. The group gave each of them seven masks, told them to wear them every day, and gave them cushions and quilts, and the PARKAS -- the ones that get wet after three days. And about 10 buckets of instant noodles per person.

A third group of volunteers, who arrived on February 23rd, were given two boxes each. Gao Qiang ate one box and kept the other for the next day.

In order to save money, they used to eat once a day, but also in the evening to eat. Fang Jian said that no fire was allowed in the corridor, so they had to cook noodles quietly at night. Walk around the park during the day, get some Sun.

A regular staff member comes every morning at eight or nine to take their temperature and give them hair masks. But they said the group was just for show, taking the temperature of the nearest person as they arrived and taking pictures of the people next to them. The instant noodles were given only one bucket, and when they were given, they were photographed. "It shows you've done your work, and the rest of the people don't care, " Fang said.

They suspect they're the ones who called the men who flushed the tunnels.

Who The hell is that? It doesn't matter to them. Their biggest problem is solving the problem.

Things soon changed.

At 10 p.m. on Feb. 24, the news that they had been flushed spread through a crowd of volunteers. Someone immediately organized a rescue party, and in the early hours of the morning, six or seven people with new quilts and sheets rushed to the vicinity of the Yellow Crane Tower.

However, there was no one in the park. According to clues, volunteers in another channel to find people, is the Fang Jian and Sheng Kuan two fellow villagers. They got quilts, and an independent documentary director carried a big bag of snacks and insisted they take them.

On the evening of February 24, volunteers gave quilts to homeless people (picture / Xiang Zhilin, reporter from Nanfengchuang) 

In the afternoon, he complained about Sheng Kuan, who took the photo. This time, he didn't refuse the shot. "I know what's good and what's bad. I don't care if you are kind, " he explained.

The director of the documentary was a young girl who sat cross-legged in the aisle, facing them. She prepared her own sheets and spent the night in the passage with them. Sheng Kuan finally opened the chatterbox and told his story with a smile. Silence, the director of a male companion suddenly singing: "My sadness to myself, your beauty let you go. " Sheng Kuan is very supportive, clapped repeatedly called "good, good. ".

Unfortunately, Gao Qiang, old Tan and five other people, never found. After dark, they would pack up and find their own "beds" , no one knows where.

Fortunately, on this night, there was still no real rain.

A good night's sleep
The next day, the afternoon of February 25, I found Gao Qiang at the Yellow Crane Tower. He slept under the bridge last night, but the weather was warm and his coat was barely enough. Late in the night, the noise on the road woke him up, he went to a river, the cotton coat washed again, ready to dry wear.

"What a pity! " He sighed and shook his head. At noon he touched his clothes, feeling dry, and took a nap under the bridge. But when I woke up, someone had taken my coat.

He had not eaten all day again, and went back to the park to wander about, and so did the others. As soon as the volunteers got the news, they started looking for a quilt to replace the four people they had missed last night.

On This Day, the authorities issued a new policy, "for those who are stranded in Hubei Province because of the control of the li-e channel and have difficulties in living, the local government and relevant parties will provide relief services. ". In other words, they can get official help.

However, the policy has not been implemented yet. Fang said he met a manager once, but instead of asking if he needed help, he reminded him that he could not live here and told him to go away.

Even when the government offered him a place to live, he did not want to go. As a professional beggar, he was reluctant to accept Welfare because he had been institutionalized in Zhejiang Province in 2004. "They kept me for a few days without good food or shelter, and made me pay 300 yuan. "

Old Tan also met the administrator, on his way back to the park, three men in uniform stopped him, said he now has a shelter, asked him to go. Old Tan replied, "No, " and hurried away from them. He told me that he was mainly worried about the fees, and secondly he was afraid of getting infected.

They prefer to stay in the park, where they can take a walk, bask in the sun, and be away from people. It's just hard to find a place to live, and around 10:00 in the morning, someone put a fence around the entrance, and everything inside was cleared out.

This afternoon, there was a new addition to the park. He was carrying a big bag, carrying a bag, dressed neatly, he was just run out of money, can not continue to stay in the hotel, so come to the park. He had come from Zhejiang, and he would not say anything more.

Around 5 p.m. , I ordered a 7-person takeout, which took an hour to arrive, and they quickly ran out. However, to find a new quilt, volunteers had to pick it up one at a time. It was getting dark and the temperature had dropped markedly.

At 8:28 pm, the volunteer weige went to the park and gave them the quilt. Gao Qiang and the others thanked him profusely, but they were running out of time to find a place to stay tonight. After a while, the crowd broke up.

At the intersection near the park, I met the garbage man again. He was carrying all his luggage and looked very tired. He said that he had found two places to live, but that they had roused him and sent him away. Unwilling to speak any more, he walked toward the Yangtze River Bridge. The intersection turned away.

Shortly after 9 p.m. , Gao Qiang finally found a new hallway and headed down to check it out. In fact, Sheng Kuan and Fang Jian sleep here, because this corridor is very remote, temporarily not noticed. Gao Qiang was happy. "I can sleep soundly tonight, " he said.

On the night of February 25th, Gao Qiang found a new passage

About ten minutes after he went down, a man in a security suit came, took one look into the tunnel, and came up. He complained to me, "they can't be called away, and they're living here again. They don't want to go when the government is taking them in. "

He is the opposite square staff, according to him, the Red Cross donated materials, he was reported after the delivery, the last two days to flush the channel, but also because of his report. "No way, they don't want to go, but the passageways are uninhabitable, that's the rule, " he said. The passageway is still uninhabitable, and he will report it tomorrow.

Some of the characters are pseudonyms

The instant noodles were given only one bucket, and when they were given, they were photographed. "It shows you've done your work, and the rest of the people don't care, " Fang said.

They suspect they're the ones who called the men who flushed the tunnels.

Who The hell is that? It doesn't matter to them. Their biggest problem is solving the problem.

Things soon changed.

At 10 p.m. on Feb. 24, the news that they had been flushed spread through a crowd of volunteers. Someone immediately organized a rescue party, and in the early hours of the morning, six or seven people with new quilts and sheets rushed to the vicinity of the Yellow Crane Tower.

However, there was no one in the park. According to clues, volunteers in another channel to find people, is the Fang Jian and Sheng Kuan two fellow villagers. They got quilts, and an independent documentary director carried a big bag of snacks and insisted they take them.

On the evening of February 24, volunteers gave quilts to homeless people (picture / Xiang Zhilin, reporter from Nanfengchuang) 

In the afternoon, he complained about Sheng Kuan, who took the photo. This time, he didn't refuse the shot. "I know what's good and what's bad. I don't care if you are kind, " he explained.

The director of the documentary was a young girl who sat cross-legged in the aisle, facing them. She prepared her own sheets and spent the night in the passage with them. Sheng Kuan finally opened the chatterbox and told his story with a smile. Silence, the director of a male companion suddenly singing: "My sadness to myself, your beauty let you go. " Sheng Kuan is very supportive, clapped repeatedly called "good, good. ".

Unfortunately, Gao Qiang, old Tan and five other people, never found. After dark, they would pack up and find their own "beds" , no one knows where.

Fortunately, on this night, there was still no real rain.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A good night's sleep

The next day, the afternoon of February 25, I found Gao Qiang at the Yellow Crane Tower. He slept under the bridge last night, but the weather was warm and his coat was barely enough. Late in the night, the noise on the road woke him up, he went to a river, the cotton coat washed again, ready to dry wear.

"What a pity! " He sighed and shook his head. At noon he touched his clothes, feeling dry, and took a nap under the bridge. But when I woke up, someone had taken my coat.

He had not eaten all day again, and went back to the park to wander about, and so did the others. As soon as the volunteers got the news, they started looking for a quilt to replace the four people they had missed last night.

On This Day, the authorities issued a new policy, "for those who are stranded in Hubei Province because of the control of the li-e channel and have difficulties in living, the local government and relevant parties will provide relief services. ". In other words, they can get official help.

However, the policy has not been implemented yet. Fang said he met a manager once, but instead of asking if he needed help, he reminded him that he could not live here and told him to go away.

Even when the government offered him a place to live, he did not want to go. As a professional beggar, he was reluctant to accept Welfare because he had been institutionalized in Zhejiang Province in 2004. "They kept me for a few days without good food or shelter, and made me pay 300 yuan. "

Old Tan also met the administrator, on his way back to the park, three men in uniform stopped him, said he now has a shelter, asked him to go. Old Tan replied, "No, " and hurried away from them. He told me that he was mainly worried about the fees, and secondly he was afraid of getting infected.

They prefer to stay in the park, where they can take a walk, bask in the sun, and be away from people. It's just hard to find a place to live, and around 10:00 in the morning, someone put a fence around the entrance, and everything inside was cleared out.

This afternoon, there was a new addition to the park. He was carrying a big bag, carrying a bag, dressed neatly, he was just run out of money, can not continue to stay in the hotel, so come to the park. He had come from Zhejiang, and he would not say anything more.

Around 5 p.m. , I ordered a 7-person takeout, which took an hour to arrive, and they quickly ran out. However, to find a new quilt, volunteers had to pick it up one at a time. It was getting dark and the temperature had dropped markedly.

At 8:28 pm, the volunteer weige went to the park and gave them the quilt. Gao Qiang and the others thanked him profusely, but they were running out of time to find a place to stay tonight. After a while, the crowd broke up.

At the intersection near the park, I met the garbage man again. He was carrying all his luggage and looked very tired. He said that he had found two places to live, but that they had roused him and sent him away. Unwilling to speak any more, he walked toward the Yangtze River Bridge. The intersection turned away.

Shortly after 9 p.m. , Gao Qiang finally found a new hallway and headed down to check it out. In fact, Sheng Kuan and Fang Jian sleep here, because this corridor is very remote, temporarily not noticed. Gao Qiang was happy. "I can sleep soundly tonight, " he said.

On the night of February 25th, Gao Qiang found a new passage

About ten minutes after he went down, a man in a security suit came, took one look into the tunnel, and came up. He complained to me, "they can't be called away, and they're living here again. They don't want to go when the government is taking them in. "

He is the opposite square staff, according to him, the Red Cross donated materials, he was reported after the delivery, the last two days to flush the channel, but also because of his report. "No way, they don't want to go, but the passageways are uninhabitable, that's the rule, " he said. The passageway is still uninhabitable, and he will report it tomorrow.
